[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:JT964.9832..QT63 KQ73.A4.Q962.A84 8.KQT75.T84.J952 A52.J6.AKJ753.K7"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "7NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
pass 1NT pass 3D pass 4D pass 4NT pass 5H pass 7NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "7e5a05fd38fdd7b0b3586e2952c94e4ea70132c3c8c61de2a0319ff31fb126ba"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/squeeze_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{North is to play 7NT. East leads the \HK.

With 12 obvious tricks your first thought should be that perhaps the \Ss will split 3-3.

Then, your second thought should be that dummy's \HJ is a Threat against East's \HQ, so if it is East who holds 4 \Ss you will be able to squeeze him.

Since the contract is 7NT you take the first trick with the \HA. 

With one trick in the bag you should test \Ds next. When you play the \DA West discards a \S.

You continue with the \DQ and \D K, West discarding a \H and a \C. 

Since West has shown up with a \D void he has become the odds-on favorite to hold the \S Guard. His \S discard makes it very likely that he started with 5 \Ss. 

To find out for sure you play \SA, then \SQ. Sure enough East discards a \H on the second round. 

You can't squeeze East in \Hs and \Ss because he doesn't hold the \S Guard, West does. 

But now a completely new possibility shows up. Say to yourself, over and over, "East must guard \Hs, and West must guard \Ss. Nobody can guard \Cs."

You start playing dummy's \D winners. 

With one more \D in dummy, things look like this. 

When you play the \D5 West must keep both \Ss to guard against your \S7. So he discards the \C6, hoping partner can stop that suit.

Your \S7 is now worthless so you throw it.

East has no problem, (yet), he discards the \H10. 

[showcards N:S5,HJ,CK,C7 E:SJ,ST,CQ,CT S:SK,CA,C8,C4 W:HQ,CJ,C9,C5]

It is now time to pressure East. 

Play dummy's \S5 to your \SK.

East MUST keep his \HQ so he releases his \C5.

And you win the last three tricks with \CK, \CA, \C8.

This is called a Double Squeeze.}
[Play "W"]HK

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AK74.AK5.KQT.AK2 QJT83.JT72.63.T6 952.6.AJ974.Q843 6.Q9843.852.J975"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "7NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2C pass 3D pass 4NT pass 5D pass 7NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "7202b0029d1efd40d9bb92459da730ad13e416caa3e9719e87d1b6d179f59339"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/squeeze_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 7NT. South leads the \SQ.

One more winner is needed. Dummy's fourth \C is a possibility.

So take the \SK and play \C A K Q.

South discards a \S on the third \C. 

Now you know North guards the \Cs.

Before tackling \Ds, see what you can discover about \Ss.

Play the \SA. North discards a \H. 

North guards the \Cs. South guards the \Ss. Nobody can guard the \Hs.

Play 4 rounds of \Ds. 

[showcards N:S9,H6,D4,C8 E:HQ,H9,H8,CJ S:S7,HA,HK,H5 W:SJ,HJ,HT,H7]

On the fourth \D North had to discard a \H. You discarded a small \S. South discarded a \S on the third \D and a \H on the fourth.

Play dummy's \D4. North cannot throw the \CJ or he will set up dummy's \C8, so he discards a \H.

You discard the \S7.

Now South is squeezed. He cannot discard the \SJ or he will set up dummy's \S9, so he discards a \H.

You win the last three \H tricks with another Double Squeeze.}
[Play "W"]SQ

